publishing_date: Date.parse("2017-09-24")
},
{
title: "B-Sides — Polish Fashion Brand You Need to Know",
subtitle: "The grass is always greener on the other side of the fence.",
summary: "In Poland we have a famous saying “You glorify the foreign, but you don’t know your own”. (The equivalent of the American proverb: “The grass is always greener on the other side of the fence.”) When it comes to appreciation of the local fashion designers in Poland, it is getting better and better but it still hard for them to compete with the strong international fashion names. Therefore, on this blog, I try from time to time, or as often as it is possible, to help keep my readers informed about the independent designers from all over the world trying to leave their mark on the international fashion arena.",
content: "<p></p><p>In Poland we have a famous saying “You glorify the foreign, but you don’t know your own”. (The equivalent of the American proverb: “The grass is always greener on the other side of the fence.”) When it comes to appreciation of the local fashion designers in Poland, it is getting better and better but it still hard for them to compete with the strong international fashion names. Therefore, on this blog, I try from time to time, or as often as it is possible, to help keep my readers informed about the independent designers from all over the world trying to leave their mark on the international fashion arena. This time I would like to introduce you to B Sides Handmade, a Polish knitwear brand with its roots in Podlasie region, very close to my heart as I was born there.</p><p><br></p><p>Basia Chrabolowska is a designer and owner of&nbsp;<a href='http://www.bsideshandmade.com/index.php' target='_blank' style='color: inherit;'>B Sides&nbsp;</a>established in 2011. The idea for this fashion undertaking was born based on a special bond between grand-mother and grand-daughter and their unique love for wool. The designer’s vision of the brand is based on quality, simplicity and functionality. She reinvents traditional hand-made craft according to the necessities of the modern times. All clothes and accessories are 100% made of alpaca and merino wool. The current collection, LA Americana FW1516 is inspired by the travels in South America.</p><p><br></p><p>When we look at the beautiful photos accompanying the campaign, we find references of the Argentinian cowboys “gauchos”, the Colombian region Cauca and vivid colors of the local folklore of Mexico and Peru. The line mostly consists of sweaters, skirts and dresses, precisely knitted by the knitwear artists in Podlasie region. The clothes are ultra feminine, minimalist and sensual. They can be worn directly on the naked skin, as merino wool has amazing qualities such as the ability to regulate the body temperature, providing warm without overheating the wearer; it is slightly moisture repellent and contains lanolin with anti-bacterial and hypoallergenic qualities and is one of the softest types of wool.</p><p><br></p><p>The pictures of the campaign of B Sides promote beauty of the Polish landscape mixed with influences of the cultures of South America. (The bracelets which are part of the collection were handmade by the local artisans in Colombia.) The entire collection was made in Poland. Fingers crossed for Basia and her super natural and tradition-curious approach to fashion!!! Please let me know who are your favorite local designers and why you think what they do is unique! Let’s try to support them through this holiday season!</p><p><br></p><p><span style='color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.84);'>B SIDES&nbsp;</span><a href='http://www.bsideshandmade.com/' target='_blank' style='color: inherit; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);'>www.bsideshandmade.com</a></p><p><em style='color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.84);'>Originally published at&nbsp;</em><a href='http://www.stylecharmer.com/2015/12/b-sides-polish-fashion-brand-you-need.html' target='_blank' style='color: inherit; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);'><em>www.stylecharmer.com</em></a><em style='color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.84);'>.</em></p><p></p>",
picture: 'http://bsideshandmade.com/shop/images/page/p1a4vevdn1uo41a1l3duh294k8a.jpg',
category_id: Category.find_by_name("Fashion").id,
user_id: User.find_by_first_name("Ania").id,
publishing_date: Date.parse("2017-09-26")
},
{
title: "Not All Who Want Repeal Want Revolution",
subtitle: "The march for women",
summary: "Last Saturday, around 30,000 people marched through the streets of Dublin on the Sixth Annual March for Choice. I was one of many who carried posters, pinned badges to coats, and chanted “hey-ho, hey-ho, the Eighth Amendment has got to go” whilst bemused groups of tourists looked on.",
content: "<p></p><p>Last Saturday, around 30,000 people marched through the streets of Dublin on the Sixth Annual March for Choice. I was one of many who carried posters, pinned badges to coats, and chanted “<em>hey-ho, hey-ho, the Eighth Amendment has got to go</em>” whilst bemused groups of tourists looked on. It was a fun experience, and my first time at a political rally or march concerned with repealing the Eighth Amendment. People were jovial, energised and proud to be marching alongside sisters, mothers and female colleagues, united in the belief that women should no longer have to suffer under such an antiquated, Byzantine amendment to the Irish Constitution.</p><p><br></p><p>One thing that did concern me however was the proliferation of hard-left groups at the march.&nbsp;<em>People Before Profit</em>,&nbsp;<em>Solidarity</em>&nbsp;and the&nbsp;<em>Socialist Worker’s Party</em>&nbsp;were all there in large numbers, as were a lot of people sympathetic to hard-left politics but maybe not attached to any one specific political party. You may think it strange that I was concerned by the appearance of such groups, especially at a march concerned with supporting a woman’s right to choose. For those of you familiar with marches that focus on social causes, it shouldn’t be a surprise to hear or see such groups at such marches — You can usually bank on them being there in fact; a march wouldn’t be complete with a communist group of one kind or another belting on about how corrupt the state is and how the workers should rise up.</p><p><br></p><p>The reason for my concern is how their appearance affects how the whole Repeal movement is seen. Now, I’m&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;saying they can’t march with us, no sir. They have every right to take advantage of that freedom. But my concern arises from the fact that their appearance — the appearance of any so-called ‘revolutionary’ group in fact — at the march could potentially hamper attempts to win over more moderate, less politically-inclined Irish men and women who are undecided in regards to whether we should repeal the Eighth Amendment, and allow free, safe and legal abortion for women to be available on this island.</p><p><br></p><p>Perception in politics is, sadly, still everything. The perception of those who want to repeal the Eighth as Trotskyite revolutionaries is one that the movement should shake if it wants to win the hearts and minds of so-called ‘middle Ireland’. Signs such as that which was tied to O’Connell Bridge, reading “<em>early risers smash the State</em>” (a reference to comments by Taoiseach Leo Varadkar), and stunts such as one by Trinity College Dublin’s&nbsp;<em>People Before Profit</em>&nbsp;branch — whereby they pulled down signs advertising a pro-life event — are incredibly unhelpful, and do not represent the vast majority of those who march for a woman’s right to choose. The latter in particular irked me the most, as the group posted (then deleted) photos of them taking down such signs as if it was some heroic act, even though it was frankly incredibly childish and an act that violated the pro-life lobby’s right to free expression.</p><p><br></p><p>I’m a proud pro-choice advocate, but I’m also somebody who is pro-market, pro-free trade and pro-EU. The hard-left are none of those things, and yet it feels as if they have a monopoly on the pro-choice ‘brand’ and its message. Not only does this turn off more moderate, less politically active voices, it also really hinders the movement when it comes to winning over undecided voices before the referendum on the Eighth next year. I’ve friends in that undecided camp, many of them women, who feel intimidated by the attitude of “<em>repeal the Eighth, no debate</em>” that currently exist within the pro-choice movement — The appearance of that movement as a revolutionary, destructive force only further intimidates them and makes them feel that (a) the movement isn’t open to them, and (b) unsure as to whether to vote to repeal the Eighth at all.</p><p><br></p><p>This piece is a call to those like me, moderates for choice. For Fine Gael, Fianna Fail, Labour and Green Party voters who are pro-choice. This movement needs you to speak up and speak louder than the voices of the revolutionary far-left. We need to make it clear that not all that want repeal are revolutionaries — We’re just ordinary, at times politically ambivalent individuals who just want to support women in Ireland by giving them a choice when it comes to abortion.</p><p></p>",
picture: 'https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/2000/1*TPH5ymetBU1yr3-umomeXA.jpeg',
category_id: Category.find_by_name("Europe").id,
user_id: User.find_by_first_name("Ruairi").id,
publishing_date: Date.parse("2017-10-04")
},
